1. Check quality of reads by FastQc
		fastqc data.fastq
		
2. Use TrimGalore to improve quality of reads
		perl trim_galore data.fastq 
		
3. Prepare genom to alignment with BS-sequencing reads
		bismark_genome_preparation --path_to_bowtie /usr/bin/bowtie2/ --verbose /data/genomes/homo_sapiens/genom/
		
4. Alignment reads to genome
	bismark --genome /data/genomes/homo_sapiens/genom/ data.fastq

5. Download genom adnotation and select information only about exons
		 awk -F"\t" '$3=="exon" {print $1"\t"$2"\t"$3"\t"$4"\t"$5" \t"$6"\t"$7"\t"$8"\t"$9'}  >exon.gft gh19.gtf
		 	
6. Use featureCounts that counts mapped reads for genomic features
		./featureCounts -a ./annotation/exon.gft -o CountedReads.gtf ~/data_bismark.bam
		
7. Use FastaParser script to get FASTA file from GTF file
		python3 FastaParser.py CT_conversion.fasta GA_conversion.fasta CountedReads.gtf

8. Use CpGwindow.py or CpGdistance.py script to get information about methylated CpG islands
		python3 CpGwindow.py example.fasta
		or
		python3 CpGdistance.py example.fasta
		
		



